{"id":"math230-dot_prod230-grad001","cid":"MATH 230","topic":"Gradient and Directional Derivatives","subtopic":"Dot product in gradient context","difficulty":2,"license":"CC BY-NC-SA (Numberbender original)","instruction":"The gradient ∇f at a point is ({a1}, {a2}, 0) and the unit direction vector is ({b1}, {b2}, 0). Compute the directional derivative D_u f = ∇f · u.","params":{"a1":{"type":"int","min":-5,"max":5},"a2":{"type":"int","min":-5,"max":5},"a3":{"type":"int","min":0,"max":0},"b1":{"type":"int","min":-3,"max":3},"b2":{"type":"int","min":-3,"max":3},"b3":{"type":"int","min":0,"max":0}},"answer_expr":"dot_prod230","steps":["D_u f = ∇f · u = ({a1})({b1}) + ({a2})({b2}) + 0.","= {answer_dot_prod230}."],"tags":["calculus-3","directional-derivative","gradient","dot-product"]}
